Three layers of JSON response assertion: (1) Schema validation: verify the structure matches the documented contract — required fields present, no undocumented extra fields (unless explicitly permitted), correct field names (case-sensitive: 'email' vs 'Email'), and correct data types (age must be a number, not a string '25'). Tools: Postman's JSON Schema validation using tv4 or ajv, or Newman with a custom schema test.
(2) Value assertions: verify specific field values are correct for the given input — the created user's email matches what was submitted, the order total matches the sum of line items, the created_at timestamp is approximately now (within a reasonable window). Postman test syntax: pm.expect(jsonBody.user.email).to.equal(requestEmail);
(3) Format validation: beyond data type, verify format correctness — dates in ISO 8601 format ('2026-07-14'), emails matching email regex, phone numbers matching the documented format, UUIDs matching UUID regex, monetary values not having floating point precision errors (compare 0.1 + 0.2 === 0.3 is false in floating point — use integer cents representation). Postman syntax: pm.expect(jsonBody.id).to.match(/^[0-9a-f]{8}-[0-9a-f]{4}-/);

The SELECT with JOIN, WHERE, GROUP BY, and HAVING chain is the most important for database testing because it exercises the core data retrieval patterns used by most application queries:
SELECT o.customer_id, COUNT(o.id) AS order_count, SUM(o.total_amount) AS total_spent FROM orders o INNER JOIN customers c ON o.customer_id = c.id WHERE o.status = 'completed' AND o.created_at >= '2026-01-01' GROUP BY o.customer_id HAVING SUM(o.total_amount) > 1000 ORDER BY total_spent DESC;
This query tests: JOIN correctness (only orders with matching customers), WHERE filtering (completed, recent orders), aggregation (COUNT, SUM), HAVING filtering on aggregated values (high-value customers), and ORDER BY. For database testing, verify: correct results on known test data, edge cases (no rows in date range → empty result, not error), NULL handling (orders with null amounts), index usage (EXPLAIN plan shows index scan, not full table scan on large tables).
